<br />

<br />
Thott has 267 total wins, and 53 of those are hard.  I don't know when he stopped taking Pet classes into his groups, or at what point he made his analysis.  I take his statements and conclusions at face value based upon his reputation for thoroughness and my general impression of his integrity and methods.
<br />

<br />
You know, though, it is data like this that could be useful.  I'd like to see we Mages get lots and lots of parses of GOOD relative DPS data and ones which also include the items you talk about above (weapons, DS, pet spells).  We could see how the Mage performs over time, level, and expansion, and have historical data to make a point when we "feel" something has changed.
<br />

<br />
For a good example of this kind of thing, check Graffe's and see the posts regarding how crits work.  There is some good, statistically valid data over there over 10's of thousands of casts that shows how crit percentages were first at one level, went up for awhile, and then were subsequently nerfed.
<br />

<br />
In any case, there is no question in my mind that the statements being made here about Mage scaling, pet scaling, and Mage scaling WITHIN THEIR OWN CLASS are often valid, and when valid are pretty disturbing considering expectations and investment into this class, and into the game.
<br />

<br />
I think it's also very hard for dev's to understand the issues without taking the ride themselves.  It's easy to theorize and cluck, and it is quite another thing to play the class daily over the course of expansions and watch the changes, feel the changes, understand the changes.
<br />

